 examines how Chicanx pop culture, capable of both liberation and exploitation, fostered interracial and transnational identities, engaged social movements, and produced varied utopian visions with divergent possibilities and limits. Grounded in the theoretical frameworks of Walter Benjamin, Stuart Hall, and the Zapatista movement, this book reveals how Chicanxs articulated pop cultural utopias to make sense of, challenge, and improve the worlds they inhabited.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChicano movementzUnited States. 0aMexican Americans and mass mediaxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican Americans and mass mediaxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aMexican Americans in popular culturexPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican Americans in popular culturexPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aMexican AmericansxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aMexican AmericansxSocial life and customsxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUtopias in mass media. 0aUtopiaszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aChicanx, popular culture, borderlands, global justice movement, border studies, Chicano history, Chicano music, Chicano music culture, Chicano art, east los angeles, media studies, cultural studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022 Englishz978311099455108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2022z9783110994520oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of